Implemented Vercel Speed Insights for the Next.js project

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` version 2.0.0 using pnpm
- Updated package.json with the new dependency
- Updated pnpm-lock.yaml with resolved dependencies

### 2. Configuration
Added SpeedInsights component to the root layout file following official Vercel documentation:
- **File Modified**: `src/app/layout.tsx`
- **Import Added**: `import { SpeedInsights } from "@vercel/speed-insights/next";`
- **Component Added**: `<SpeedInsights />` component placed in the body alongside existing Analytics component

## Implementation Details

Following the official Vercel Speed Insights quickstart guide (https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart), I:

1. Used the Next.js-specific import path (`@vercel/speed-insights/next`) which is optimized for Next.js App Router
2. Placed the component at the root layout level to ensure it tracks all pages
3. Positioned it alongside the existing `<Analytics />` component for consistency
4. Preserved all existing code structure, theme handling, and functionality

## Verification

All verification steps completed successfully:
- ✅ Build completed without errors (pnpm run build)
- ✅ Linter passed with no new warnings (pnpm run lint)
- ✅ TypeScript type checking passed (pnpm run typecheck)
- ✅ No breaking changes introduced

## Next Steps

After deployment to Vercel:
1. Enable Speed Insights in the Vercel Dashboard for this project
2. Deploy the changes using `vercel deploy`
3. Visit the application to generate initial metrics
4. Monitor performance data in the Vercel Speed Insights dashboard

Speed Insights will now automatically track Core Web Vitals and other performance metrics for all pages in the application.
